Diagn√≥stico e consertos para modelos lineares

Problemas poss√≠veis

  1. Non-linearity of the response-predictor relationships.
  2. Correlation of error terms.
  3. Non-constant variance of error terms.
  4. Outliers.
  5. High-leverage points.
  6. Collinearity.

N√£o linearidade na rela√ß√£o entre preditores e vari√°vel de resposta

Caso 1

auto = select(Auto, mpg, horsepower)
ggpairs(auto)

automodel = lm(mpg ~ horsepower, data = auto)
tidy(automodel, conf.int = TRUE)
glance(automodel)
grid = auto %>% 
  add_predictions(model = automodel)
ggplot(grid, aes(horsepower)) + 
  geom_point(aes(y = mpg), alpha = .8) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = pred), colour = "red", size = 1) 

autoplot(automodel)

Uma solu√ß√£o poss√≠vel √© tentar polin√¥mios de grau mais alto, que t√™m curva.

ggpairs(auto)

automodel = lm(mpg ~ horsepower + I(horsepower^2), data = auto)
grid = auto %>% 
  mutate(horsepower2 = horsepower^2) %>% 
  add_predictions(model = automodel)
ggplot(grid, aes(horsepower)) + 
  geom_point(aes(y = mpg), alpha = .8) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = pred), colour = "red", size = 1) 

autoplot(automodel)

tidy(automodel)
glance(automodel)

Caso 2

(Na minha experi√™ncia, esse √© mais comum)

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .2)

# Bonus: geom_hex!
ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
  geom_hex()

caratmodel = lm(price ~ carat, data = diamonds)
grid = diamonds %>% 
  add_predictions(model = caratmodel) %>% 
  add_residuals(caratmodel)
ggplot(grid, aes(x = carat)) + 
  geom_hex(aes(y = price)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = pred), colour = "red", size = 1) 

grid %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = carat)) + 
  geom_ref_line(h = 0, colour = "grey80") + 
  geom_point(aes(y = resid), size = 1, alpha = .3)

grid %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = price)) + 
  geom_ref_line(h = 0, colour = "grey80") + 
  geom_point(aes(y = resid), size = 1, alpha = .3)

# autoplot(caratmodel)

Solu√ß√£o: Transformar as vari√°veis para que elas passem a ter uma rela√ß√£o mais linear. √â um processo de tentativa e erro a partir dos formatos observados. Por exemplo, se o formado de \(y = f(x)\) √© tal que y cresce exponencialmente com x (ou seja, \(y = ae^{bx}\)), e transformamos \(y\) com log, temos que \(ln(y) = ln(ae^{bx}) = ln(a) + bx\). Essa express√£o modela uma rela√ß√£o linear entre \(ln(y)\) e \(x\).

J√° se a rela√ß√£o \(y = f(x)\) √© no formato \(y = ax^{b}\)) podemos transformar \(x\) e \(y\) com log, temos que \(ln(y) = ln(ax^{b}) = ln(a) + b log(x)\). Essa express√£o modela uma rela√ß√£o linear entre \(ln(y)\) e \(ln(x)\).

A mesma l√≥gica pode ser usada para logaritmos em outras bases e para ra√≠zes quadr√°ticas ou outras transformadas. As transforma√ß√µes mais comuns a considerar s√£o log(x), sqrt(x), exp(x) e \(x^2\).

Aplicando para o caso dos diamantes:

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = log(carat), y = log(price))) +
  geom_point(alpha = .2)

diamonds2 = diamonds %>% 
  transmute(carat = log(carat), 
            price = log(price))
caratmodel = lm(price ~ carat, data = diamonds2)
grid = diamonds2 %>% 
  add_predictions(model = caratmodel) %>% 
  add_residuals(model = caratmodel)
ggplot(grid, aes(x = carat)) + 
  geom_hex(aes(y = price)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = pred), colour = "red", size = 1) 

grid %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = carat)) + 
  geom_ref_line(h = 0, colour = "grey80") + 
  geom_point(aes(y = resid), size = .5, alpha = .3)

grid %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = price)) + 
  geom_ref_line(h = 0, colour = "grey80") + 
  geom_point(aes(y = resid), size = .5, alpha = .3)

# autoplot(caratmodel)

Non-constant variance of error terms

Transforma√ß√µes ou weighted least squares.

advertising = read_csv("../dados/Advertising.csv") %>% rename(campaign = X1)
Missing column names filled in: 'X1' [1]Parsed with column specification:
cols(
  X1 = col_integer(),
  TV = col_double(),
  Radio = col_double(),
  Newspaper = col_double(),
  Sales = col_double()
)
advertising %>% 
  select(-campaign) %>% 
  ggpairs(lower = list(continuous = wrap("points", alpha = 0.3)), progress = FALSE)

tv.model = lm(Sales ~ TV, data = advertising)
adv_augmented = advertising %>% 
  add_predictions(tv.model) %>% 
  add_residuals(tv.model)
# Modelo x dados
p_md = adv_augmented %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = TV)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = pred), size = 2, colour = "blue") + 
  geom_point(aes(y = Sales))
# Res√≠duos x preditor
p_rp = adv_augmented %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = TV)) + 
  geom_ref_line(h = 0, colour = "grey80") + 
  geom_point(aes(y = resid), size = 2) 
# Res√≠duos x vari√°vel de resposta
p_rr = adv_augmented %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Sales)) + 
  geom_ref_line(h = 0, colour = "grey80") + 
  geom_point(aes(y = resid), size = 2)
gridExtra::grid.arrange(p_md, p_rp, p_rr, ncol = 2)

tv.model2 = lm(log(Sales) ~ log(TV), data = advertising)
adv_augmented = advertising %>% 
  add_predictions(tv.model2) %>% 
  add_residuals(tv.model2)
# Modelo x dados
p_md = adv_augmented %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = TV)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = exp(pred)), size = 2, colour = "blue") + 
  geom_point(aes(y = Sales))
# Res√≠duos x preditor
p_rp = adv_augmented %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = TV)) + 
  geom_ref_line(h = 0, colour = "grey80") + 
  geom_point(aes(y = resid), size = 2) 
# Res√≠duos x vari√°vel de resposta
p_rr = adv_augmented %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Sales)) + 
  geom_ref_line(h = 0, colour = "grey80") + 
  geom_point(aes(y = resid), size = 2)
gridExtra::grid.arrange(p_md, p_rp, p_rr, ncol = 2)

Outliers e High-leverage points

Uma boa: http://setosa.io/ev/ordinary-least-squares-regression/

No plot de studentized residuals, pontos com res√≠duos normalizados maiores que 3 s√£o suspeitos.

Para leverage, o adequado √© olhar pontos com leverage muito acima dos demais, ou maior que (p + 1)/n. (p sendo o n√∫mero de preditores.)
